<TITLE> Banks drive European shares up early </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Dec 20 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European shares edged higher in early trade on Thursday, led by banks including HSBC as investors awaited the next injection of liquidity from the Federal Reserve and more quarterly earnings. By 0810 GMT the FTSEurofirst 300 index of top European shares was up 0.1 percent at 1,484.35 points, having fallen by 0.46 percent on Wednesday. The Fed's special auction aimed at unclogging the credit markets met with good demand on Wednesday. The central bank is set to auction another $20 billion on Thursday. "There still is a lot of nervousness and although (the central banks) are providing a short-term salve to the interbank (market), the underlying question is still one of confidence in the markets," said Justin Urquart Stewart, a director at 7 Investment Management. "It is a very welcoming thawing of some of the ice in that market but nonetheless, I don't think anyone wants to stop on to it yet." HSBC shares were among the top positive weights on the broader European market, rising 0.6 percent, while Spain's Banco Santander and Royal Bank of Scotland both gained 0.7 percent ahead of results from US investment bank Bear Stearns later in the day. Rising crude oil prices pushed up shares in Total and Royal Dutch Shell by 0.6 and 0.8 percent, respectively. Around Europe, London's FTSE 100 index rose 0.2 percent, Frankfurt's DAX added 0.1 percent and Paris' CAC 40 was up 0.2 percent. Advancing shares on the broader European index outnumbered decliners by about 2 to
